---
import Base from "../layouts/Base.astro";
---

<Base
  title="Use Cases — Pyrite"
  description="How teams use Pyrite for software projects, research, personal knowledge, and team wikis"
>
  <section class="px-6 py-20 max-w-4xl mx-auto">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mb-4">Use cases</h1>
    <p class="text-text-secondary text-lg mb-16">
      Pyrite's typed entries, plugin system, and AI integration adapt to
      different knowledge domains. Here's how teams are using it.
    </p>

    <div class="space-y-20">
      <!-- Software Teams -->
      <div id="software">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
          <span
            class="inline-block text-xs font-mono px-2 py-0.5 rounded bg-surface-overlay text-pyrite-400"
            >software-kb</span
          >
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Software teams</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Architecture Decision Records, component documentation, prioritized
          backlogs, coding standards, and runbooks — all as structured,
          validated entries in git. Your AI pair programmer reads the project KB
          through MCP and has full context on every decision, every component,
          every backlog item.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-surface-raised rounded-xl border border-white/5 p-6 font-mono text-sm space-y-1">
          <p class="text-text-muted"># Your AI pair programmer knows your architecture</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite sw adrs</p>
          <p class="text-text-muted pl-4">16 Architecture Decision Records</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite sw components</p>
          <p class="text-text-muted pl-4">24 documented services and modules</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite sw backlog --status planned</p>
          <p class="text-text-muted pl-4">Prioritized, effort-estimated, dependency-mapped</p>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-muted text-sm mt-4">
          Pyrite itself uses this workflow — its own backlog, ADRs, and component docs
          live in a Pyrite KB. Dogfooding all the way down.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Research & Investigations -->
      <div id="research">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
          <span
            class="inline-block text-xs font-mono px-2 py-0.5 rounded bg-surface-overlay text-pyrite-400"
            >cascade</span
          >
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Research & investigations</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Track people, organizations, events, and relationships across
          hundreds of sources. Timeline visualization shows when things happened.
          The knowledge graph reveals connections between entities that aren't
          obvious from any single document. Every claim links back to a source.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-surface-raised rounded-xl border border-white/5 p-6 font-mono text-sm space-y-1">
          <p class="text-text-muted"># Structured investigation</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite create --type person --title "Jane Doe" \</p>
          <p class="pl-6">--body "CFO at Acme Corp since 2023. Previously at Initech."</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite search "financial connections" --mode hybrid</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite timeline --from 2023-01 --to 2024-06</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Personal Knowledge -->
      <div id="personal">
        <div class="flex items-center gap-3 mb-4">
          <span
            class="inline-block text-xs font-mono px-2 py-0.5 rounded bg-surface-overlay text-pyrite-400"
            >zettelkasten</span
          >
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold">Personal knowledge management</h2>
        </div>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Zettelkasten-style note-taking with a maturity workflow: fleeting
          notes become literature notes become permanent notes. Wikilinks
          connect ideas. Semantic search finds conceptually related notes you
          forgot you wrote. AI helps surface connections and suggests links.
        </p>
        <div class="bg-surface-raised rounded-xl border border-white/5 p-6 font-mono text-sm space-y-1">
          <p class="text-text-muted"># Capture, connect, develop</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite create --type zettel --title "Thinking in Systems" \</p>
          <p class="pl-6">--body "Meadows argues that system behavior..." --tags reading</p>
          <p><span class="text-pyrite-400">$</span> pyrite search "feedback loops" --mode semantic</p>
          <p class="text-text-muted pl-4"># Finds related notes across all your reading</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Team Wikis -->
      <div id="teams">
        <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-4">Team wikis</h2>
        <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6 leading-relaxed">
          Replace Notion or Confluence with something you own. Structured
          entries with wikilinks, collections with kanban/table/gallery views,
          a web UI your whole team can use, and AI features powered by
          bring-your-own-key. Deploy on a $6/month VPS with Docker —
          unlimited users, no per-seat pricing.
        </p>
        <div class="grid sm:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
          <div class="bg-surface-raised rounded-lg border border-white/5 p-4 text-center">
            <div class="text-pyrite-400 font-semibold">Notion Team</div>
            <div class="text-2xl font-bold mt-1">$10<span class="text-sm text-text-muted font-normal">/user/mo</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-surface-raised rounded-lg border border-white/5 p-4 text-center">
            <div class="text-pyrite-400 font-semibold">Confluence</div>
            <div class="text-2xl font-bold mt-1">$6<span class="text-sm text-text-muted font-normal">/user/mo</span></div>
          </div>
          <div class="bg-surface-raised rounded-lg border border-pyrite-500/30 p-4 text-center">
            <div class="text-pyrite-400 font-semibold">Pyrite</div>
            <div class="text-2xl font-bold mt-1">$6<span class="text-sm text-text-muted font-normal">/mo total</span></div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</Base>
